I've set a breakpoint on the StreamsProxy#kill() call in the finally-block and also added a break point on line 247 in OutputStreamMonitor with the following condition:

 System.out.println("read: " + read); return false;

thus I should see the number of bytes read by each iteration of the loop. What I can see is that there are several times that there is above 10 bytes read (normal line of output), and the final output of the added conditional break point for each test case is -1.
In the documentation for InputStream#read(byte[]), the following paragraph is written:

 If no byte is available because the stream is at the end of the file, the value -1 is returned; otherwise, at least one byte is read and stored into b.

I suppose this means that there should be no exception when you hit EOF and thus, the sequence should be identical to when the application exits on it's own without being asked to terminate.



Before someone asks to put the reproducer as part of the unit tests; while I love to do that, it would mean that we were going to introduce a dependency from platform to CDT, and I don't think that's a good idea. Unless there is another way than the CDT way to properly handle signals from the JRE, I think the test for this needs to be manual.
